# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: astemo
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:astemo/acura-ar24e-engine] The **Acura AR24e** **engine** is a twin-turbocharged, four-stroke, 2.4-liter, V6 racing engine, made by Honda Racing Corporation USA (HRC US) for use in their Acura ARX-06 LMDh race car, since 2023.
[src:astemo/acura-ar24e-engine] Honda Performance Development, now Honda Racing Corporation USA, developed the bespoke engine for the new-for-2023 ARX-06 LMDh featuring the smallest displacement that HRC US has made for an endurance racing engine.
[src:astemo/acura-ar24e-engine] Optimizations include the 90° V-angle, to reduce the center of gravity of the engine and the combustion chamber can use sustainable low-carbon fuel.
[src:astemo/acura-ar24e-engine] In accordance with the LMDh rules, the AR24e internal combustion engine is connected to the standardized hybrid drivetrain components provided by Bosch (motor generator unit), Williams Advanced Engineering (battery pack), and an Xtrac P1359 gearbox.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] The **Acura ARX-01**, later known as the **HPD ARX-01**, is a series of Le Mans Prototypes built for sports car racing, specifically in the American Le Mans Series, Le Mans Series, and at the 24 Hours of Le Mans.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] It is the first purpose-built race car by the Acura division of Honda Motor Company, part of their multi-year program to eventually compete in endurance racing.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] The car debuted in 2007 in the American Le mans Series before expanding to customers in Europe.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] Over the years various specifications of the ARX-01 chassis have been developed, each signified by a letter suffix.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] In 2010 Acura withdrew their name from the program and Honda Performance Development which developed the car for Acura continued the program into 2011.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] At the 2006 North American International Auto Show in Detroit, Acura officially announced their plans to develop a Le Mans Prototype program for the American Le Mans Series, competing in the LMP2 class for the initial year of competition in 2007.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] Acura announced they would be using customer chassis from Lola Cars International of the United Kingdom and Courage Compétition of France, while the engine would be built entirely by Honda Performance Development of the United States.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] Acura planned to use the customer chassis for the first year, then to build their own chassis for 2008, followed by another new chassis for a move to the top LMP1 class in 2009.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] At the Detroit auto show, Acura showed their first customer chassis, a brand new Courage LC75.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] Following the announcement of the three teams involved in the project, Acura announced that for 2007 each team would concentrate on a certain aspect of development for the planned 2008 car.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] Andretti Green Racing and Highcroft Racing would use Courage LC75 chassis, and work on chassis design and aerodynamic modification.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] The third team, Fernández Racing, would use a Lola chassis and concentrate on developing the new Acura V8 engine.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] A third Courage LC75 would be retained by Honda of America for use as a developmental prototype.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] By early 2007, all three teams had begun testing their cars as well as beginning modification.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] By the time the American Le Mans Series opening round at the 12 Hours of Sebring arrived, the two Courage LC75 teams had modified their chassis to such an extent that Acura applied for homologation from the International Motor Sports Association (IMSA) and Automobile Club de l'Ouest (ACO).
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] With the application approved, the Acura Courage LC75s were renamed as Acura ARX-01a.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] As for the engine, Honda Performance Development (HPD) created a new 3.4-liter V8, the maximum size allowed by the rules, the first V8 ever branded as an Acura as well as the first motor built entirely in the United States by Honda.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] Elements of the Acura V8, dubbed the AL7R, share similar architecture with the Honda engine used in the Indy Racing League although none of the parts are interchangeable.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] The two new Acura ARX-01as, along with the other Lola team car, debuted at the 2007 12 Hours of Sebring after much preparation.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] Battling not only the Porsche squads in their own class, they also attempted to compete with the Audi R10 diesels in the higher LMP1 class throughout the race.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] During the race the ARX-01a showed the ability to at least keep close to the Audi, yet was unable to truly fight for the lead.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] However, in the end the Acura ARX-01a of Andretti Green Racing was able to survive the race better than other competitors and managed to take the class victory, as well as second place overall.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] The second ARX-01a of Highcroft Racing took sixth place overall, while the Acura-powered Lola of Fernández Racing took third.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] In the third race of the season at Long Beach, Acura gained their first overall pole, with the Andretti Green Racing ARX-01a outpacing the two Penske Racing Porsche RS Spyders and the Audi R10s.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] On July 12, 2008, the #9 Patrón Highcroft Racing ARX-01 earned Acura's first-ever overall victory in the American Le Mans Series.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] David Brabham and Scott Sharp started the Highcroft entry from pole, and managed to retake the lead from the #7 Penske Racing Porsche RS Spyder in the final 90 seconds of the Northeast Grand Prix.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] This was followed by a second overall win at the Detroit Sports Car Challenge, this time led by Andretti Green Racing's Franck Montagny and James Rossiter.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] The Acura ARX-01b won six of the eleven races in the LMP2 class for 2008, with four for Highcroft and two for Andretti Green.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] Highcroft was ranked second in the Teams Championship, Andretti Green fourth, Fernandez fifth, and de Ferran sixth.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] Acura lost the LMP2 constructors championship to Porsche by a single point.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] In 2009, Fernandez Racing continued to compete with an updated version of the ARX-01, while Acura unveiled an LMP1 class ARX-02 for Highcroft Racing and de Ferran Motorsports.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] By the end of the season, Fernandez Racing won the LMP2 teams', drivers' and manufacturers' championship.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] For 2010, Highcroft Racing has discontinued its campaign of the LMP1-spec ARX-02 and returns to an upgraded version of the ARX-01.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] The car also made its debut in Europe, in the Le Mans Series, run by Strakka Racing.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] Both teams will run the ARX-01c at Le Mans, however, Highcroft Racing will continue to use the higher-downforce ARX-01b configuration in the American Le Mans Series until after the Le Mans 24 Hours.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] Highcroft faced stiff competition but was able to beat the Cytosport Porsche by 20 points despite running a 25 kg series-imposed ballast.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] The team won 4 victories and extended the points lead further when Cytosport was absent from Lime Rock due to a crash.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] Drayson Racing and Dyson Racing also ran in ALMS and had a straight-line speed advantage over Highcroft, becoming most obvious in the Miller Motosport Park.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] Strakka's HPD in the Le Mans Series proved to be superior to the opposition in class.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] In all of the 5 races in the series, the car was at least 2 seconds quicker than their nearest rival.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] A 7-minute repair would not stop them from winning at Paul Ricard.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] They also won LMP2 at Silverstone despite accidents and won overall at Hungaroring.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] The win at Hungary was the first ever in LMS history that an LMP2 car finished ahead of LMP1.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] However 2 DNFs out of 5 races meant that Strakka missed out on the championship to the more consistent RML team, who ran a Lola chassis with an HPD engine.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] Both Strakka and Highcroft competed at Le Mans for 2010, with the latter running a conservative pace for the unproven reliability.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] Ironically it was the Highcroft that was dodged with water leak issues.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] Strakka had already experimented with low-downforce aero in LMS and got the better hand.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] They set a new LMP2 class lap record, led from pole to finish, won the LMP2 class, finished 5th overall (best result ever for an LMP2) and won the Michelin Green X Challenge across all class.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] Highcroft Racing originally intended to compete in the ALMS LMP1 category using the ARX-01e powered by the HPD 3.4-liter V8 engine.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] The team took delivery only a week before the Sebring 12 Hours but was able to convert it into a 2nd-place finish.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] Highcroft did not appear at the Long Beach round and begun to take more serious involvement in the IRL program.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] On May 16, Highcroft finally announced the end of their partnership with Honda, citing the earthquake in Japan that eventually caused financial troubles at Honda.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] The ARX-01e will not appear at Le Mans and will not be raced anymore.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] Only RML and Strakka were left to campaign the ARX-01d in the Le Mans Series.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] The ARX-01d, fitted with HPD's new LMP2 stock-block V6 engine, had been run in the Le Mans Series and at Le Mans by defending Le Mans LMP2 winners Strakka Racing and by defending LMS LMP2 champions RML.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] At the Paul Ricard test the cars were very slow due to the level of engine development prior to homologation.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] RML stated that they were literally the slowest car of the whole field, and that "there's not a class out there that can't drive by us on the straight".
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] They did mention that the car was not in low drag configuration so the car was not in an optimally efficient condition.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] The ACO increased the restrictor for both cars by 1.2% before the 1000 km of Spa, but both RML and Strakka were still slower than the Nissans.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] RML did not get to start the race due to a collision with the #9 Peugeot in one of the practice sessions.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] Level 5 Motorsports announced they will now utilize the HPD ARX-01gs, Honda's cost-capped chassis and engine combination, in the remaining 2011 American Le Mans Series and Intercontinental Le Mans Cup rounds.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] Designed and developed by Wirth Research in Bicester in the UK, the car made an instant impression winning the LMP2 class on debut at the Laguna Seca six-hours and then even more impressively two weeks later at Road Atlanta's 1000-mile Petit Le Mans.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] (key) Races in **bold** indicates pole position.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] Races in *italics* indicates fastest lap.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-01] † Did not finish the race but was classified as they completed more than 70% of the race distance.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-02a] The **Acura ARX-02a** was a Le Mans Prototype constructed by Acura for competition in the LMP1 category of the American Le Mans Series.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-02a] It was Acura's second Le Mans Prototype, following their ARX-01 which competed in the LMP2 category.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-02a] Unlike the ARX-01, the ARX-02 is a bespoke LMP designed entirely for Acura by Wirth Research.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-02a] The original 3.4L V8 was expanded to 4 liters for more durability and drivability with the larger power developed with P1 rules.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-02a] Wirth Research developed a chassis to generate as much mechanical grip to overcome the power deficit to Diesel centric rules created by the ACO by exploiting the engine's low mass (low compared to larger Diesel engines).
[src:astemo/acura-arx-02a] Rear tires are now fitted onto the front of the car, increasing the contact patch by 7%, indicating that the vehicle center of mass was more forward placed than its contemporaries.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-02a] The ARX-02a were campaigned by two teams, de Ferran Motorsport (Gil de Ferran, Simon Pagenaud and Scott Dixon) and Highcroft Racing (David Brabham, Scott Sharp and Dario Franchitti), and made its competition debut at the 2009 12 Hours of Sebring.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-02a] Scott Dixon put the de Ferran entry on pole position at Sebring ahead of all the diesels of Audi and Peugeot due to slippery but dry track conditions.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-02a] However, within the first corner of the race Acura were overcome by Allan McNish in the Audi.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-02a] Neither Acura finished the race due to mechanical issues and never featured as a threat to win the race, lapping at 2.5 seconds off the winning pace.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-02a] Throughout the ALMS, the Acura gained overall wins until the Petit Le Mans.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-02a] In all of the races, the bigger tires took longer to warm up than most competitors resulting in position loss to the turbo charged P1 Lola's at race starts and restarts.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-02a] Scott Sharp crashed heavily at Petit Le Mans and the team spent the next 24 hours rebuilding the car with assistance from de Ferran.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-02a] At the final race at Laguna Seca, Gil de Ferran won a hard-fought battle with the Fernandez ARX-01.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-02a] In 2010, de Ferran closed shop and Highcroft was forced to abandon the car, ending the career of the ARX-02.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-02a] Highcroft returned to campaigning an updated version of the existing ARX-01 for the combined LMP class in 2010.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] The **Acura ARX-05** is a Daytona Prototype International (DPi) sports prototype racing car developed by Honda Performance Development (HPD) in collaboration with Oreca.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] The car began use in 2018 and was designed in accordance with IMSA’s DPi regulations which had debuted the year prior, being based on the Oreca 07 LMP2 chassis.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] The ARX-05 first competed in the IMSA Weathertech Sportscar Championship in a factory-backed effort with Team Penske before being raced by customer teams Wayne Taylor Racing and Meyer Shank Racing.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] The ARX-05 marked Acura’s return to competition in North American prototype racing following previous programs under the HPD name.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] In its five seasons of competition from 2018 to 2022, the ARX-05 would find consistent success in IMSA competition, being a regular fixture in championship fights and winning a number of races.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] With DPi regulations replaced by Le Mans Daytona h (LMDh) regulations from 2023 onwards, the ARX-05 was retired and replaced by the Acura ARX-06.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] HPD's previous efforts in IMSA prototype competition had ended under difficult circumstances.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] In 2014, the ARX-03, a predecessor to the ARX-05, was withdrawn from later races by Extreme Speed Motorsports due to complaints regarding IMSA’s Balance of Performance (BoP).
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] By 2015, with Extreme Speed Motorsports reducing its IMSA campaign to endurance events only, HPD's participation in the series was likewise limited with the newly developed ARX-04b.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] The ARX-04b proved to be a significant failure, competing only in the 2015 24 Hours of Daytona before being shelved for the older ARX-03, which itself would contest only one additional IMSA race before Extreme Speed Motorsports cancelled the remainder of its 2015 campaign.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] The ARX-04b would not compete again despite continued development and testing.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] Hoping to move on from previous setbacks, HPD would begin preparations for its next IMSA prototype as new regulations for LMP2 prototypes for 2017 were finalized alongside IMSA’s DPi ruleset.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] With the car being run under the Acura brand for the first time since 2011, HPD conducted multiple interviews with multiple different chassis manufacturers before ultimately reaching an agreement with Oreca to utilize the Oreca 07 as the basis for the ARX-05.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] HPD and Acura’s design team would work in tandem to develop the car.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] Acura’s return to IMSA prototype competition was formally announced on 11 July 2017, with HPD having reached an agreement with Team Penske to campaign the car from the 2018 season onwards.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] The ARX-05 was publicly unveiled at Laguna Seca on 18 August 2017.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] The ARX-05 is constructed around the Oreca 07’s carbon-fiber monocoque chassis.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] Acura-specific bodywork and exterior styling were developed by Acura Design Studio in California in collaboration with HPD and Oreca engineers.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] The car incorporates Acura’s signature “Jewel Eye” headlight styling from their production cars while retaining the standardized cockpit dimensions and survival cell structure mandated by the new LMP2 regulations for all DPi entries.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] Power is supplied by the Acura AR35TT, also known as the Honda HR35TT, a twin-turbocharged 3.5-liter V6 engine developed and assembled by HPD.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] The engine had previously been used in endurance prototypes competing under differing regulations, including the Ligier JS P2 and Riley MkXXVI.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] The AR35TT is derived from Honda's J35 production engine found in multiple road cars.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] Power output is regulated by IMSA BoP adjustments in a rear mid-engine, rear wheel drive layout.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] The ARX-05 features a paddle-shifting six-speed sequential gearbox supplied by Xtrac alongside an independent double-wishbone pushrod suspension at all four corners.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] Braking is provided by Brembo six-piston brake calipers acting on carbon brake rotors.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] The initial shakedown of the ARX-05 was carried out at Circuit Paul Ricard in late July 2017, prior to the car’s official public unveiling.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] Footage of the test was later used in a teaser released by Acura on August 8.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] Testing efforts expanded following the car’s transport to the United States.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] The ARX-05 completed its first North American test at Road Atlanta on 25 August 2017, with Juan Pablo Montoya driving over the course of two days.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] The car later completed its first test on Daytona International Speedway's banking on 3 November 2017, a month ahead of IMSA's official test days at the track in December.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] For the ARX-05's debut season in the 2018 IMSA SportsCar Championship, Team Penske would campaign two entries: the No.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] 6 ran by Juan Pablo Montoya and Dane Cameron full-time with Simon Pagenaud in for endurance rounds and the No.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] 7 ran by Helio Castroneves and Ricky Taylor full-time with Graham Rahal in for endurance rounds.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] Both cars would achieve moderate success throughout the season.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] Mechanical problems and race damage would plague both teams at the 24 Hours of Daytona and 12 Hours of Sebring, preventing consistent results among the Prototype class.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] Montoya would secure the team's first pole position at Long Beach as performance steadily improved.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] The breakthrough came at Mid-Ohio, where the ARX-05 achieved its maiden victory with the No.
