[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] Following another strong showing at Belle Isle, a double podium, Team Penske would struggle to maintain the same level of success for the rest of the season.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] 6 would record additional podium finishes but continued to suffer from reliability problems.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] 7 would fail to return to the podium after Belle Isle, stringing together multiple poor results.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] The team led the most laps at the Petit Le Mans, but a late race drive-through penalty dropped them to 5th.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] 7 teams would finish 5th and 7th in team standings respectively, with Acura finishing 2nd in Manufacturer standings in their debut season with the ARX-05.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] For the 2019 IMSA SportsCar Championship, Team Penske retained the No.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] 6 lineup of Juan Pablo Montoya, Dane Cameron, and Simon Pagenaud for the endurance rounds.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] Alexander Rossi replaced Graham Rahal as the No.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] 7's third driver for the endurance races, with Rahal returning only for Petit Le Mans.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] The ARX-05 would find greater success in 2019 following its inconsistent debut season.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] 6 encountered early setbacks at the 24 Hours of Daytona and 12 Hours of Sebring, finishing sixth and ninth respectively.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] 7, meanwhile, would achieve a podium at Daytona.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] A double podium at Long Beach would mark a turnaround for Team Penske, with the No.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] 6 rebounding to record seven straight podium finishes, including three wins at Mid-Ohio, Belle Isle, and Laguna Seca respectively.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] 7 failed to record a victory but stayed in championship contention, achieving five podiums with only one finish below 5th.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] The ARX-05 saw three more double podiums throughout the year.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] 6 became IMSA's 2019 champion for team competition while the No.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] Acura, meanwhile, won their first manufacturer's championship in DPi and the first with the ARX-05.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] The driver lineups remained unchanged for the 2020 IMSA SportsCar Championship, with the only change being Alexander Rossi serving as the No.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] The fortunes of the two Team Penske entries varied greatly throughout 2020.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] 7 finished 4th and 8th respectively at the 24 Hours of Daytona prior to the postponement of the season due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] Following IMSA's return to racing at the Weathertech 240, the No.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] 6 would string together multiple mediocre finishes, rebounding later on in the season to achieve three podiums in the final three races.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] 7, following poor results at the Weathertech 240 and Sebring, dominated the latter half of the season, winning four out of the last six races.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] Acura and Team Penske successfully defended their titles in 2020, with the No.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] 7 winning the team's championship by one point and Acura narrowly edging out Cadillac to take the manufacturer's championship.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] 6 would only finish 7th in the team's championship due to inconsistency.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] The 2020 season also marked the final campaign of the Acura Team Penske partnership.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] It was announced on 20 July 2020 that they would part ways following the conclusion of the season after three years of competition.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] Beginning in the 2021 IMSA SportsCar Championship, factory support for the ARX-05 was assumed by Wayne Taylor Racing and Meyer Shank Racing, the two teams campaigning the No.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] Despite the shift in team structure, the ARX-05 would see multiple drivers return to continue racing with the car.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] Ricky Taylor, Alexander Rossi, and Helio Castroneves reunited as teammates at the 24 Hours of Daytona; Taylor raced the car full-time, Rossi raced at endurance rounds, and Castroneves ran Daytona only.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] Filipe Albuquerque was signed to be the second full-time driver.
