[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] Likewise, Acura finished 2nd to Cadillac in the manufacturer's championship.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] The 2022 IMSA SportsCar Championship marked the final season for both the DPi regulations and the ARX-05.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] Wayne Taylor Racing retained Ricky Taylor and Filipe Albuqerque as full-time drivers, while Alexander Rossi returned for the 24 Hours of Daytona.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] Will Stevens joined the lineup at Daytona and Sebring, while Brendon Hartley competed at Road Atlanta.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] Meyer Shank Racing, introduced a new full-time lineup of Tom Blomqvist and Oliver Jarvis in the No.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] Helio Castroneves returned for Daytona and Road America, Simon Pagenaud returned at Daytona, and Stoffel Vandoorne filled out the lineup for Sebring.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] With the remainder of the DPi field consisting exclusively of Cadillac entries, the Acura teams remained competitive throughout the season.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] 60 opened the season by giving the ARX-05 its second victory in the 24 Hours of Daytona, topping a double podium with the No.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] 10 amassed five wins throughout the season at Daytona qualifying, Laguna Seca, Mid-Ohio, Watkins Glen, and Road America, respectively, becoming the winningest team in DPi for the season.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] 60, meanwhile, would not win again until the 2022 Petit Le Mans, but strung together five straight second-place finishes.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] 60 secured the DPi team's championship despite winning only two races, with its consistency proving decisive overall.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] 10 finished second in the standings despite claiming five victories.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] Both Acura entries finished ahead of every Cadillac in the teams' standings despite being outnumbered in the DPi field.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] As a result, Acura won the Manufacturer's championship once again, the win being the third for the ARX-05, tying them with Cadillac for most manufacturer's victories of IMSA's DPi era with one less season of competition.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] Results in **bold** indicate pole position.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-05] Results in *italics* indicate fastest lap.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-06] The **Acura ARX-06** is a sports prototype racing car designed by Honda Racing Corporation USA, formerly known as Honda Performance Development (HPD), and built by Oreca.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-06] It is designed to the Le Mans Daytona h regulations, and competes in the GTP class in the IMSA SportsCar Championship since 2023.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-06] The car has a bespoke 2.4-liter twin-turbocharged V6 engine designated as the AR24e.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-06] The ARX-06 debuted alongside the BMW M Hybrid V8, Cadillac V-LMDh and Porsche 963 at the 2023 season opener of the IMSA SportsCar Championship at the Daytona International Speedway.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-06] The ARX-06 won the 24 Hours of Daytona in 2023, the 12 Hours of Sebring in 2024 and Petit Le Mans in 2023, becoming the first car to win all three major IMSA endurance races during the GTP era.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-06] In January 2021, Acura formally announced they would participate in IMSA's new GTP class in 2023 using an LMDh-compliant racing design.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-06] On December 6, 2021, Acura announced it would work with Oreca as their chassis supplier, making Acura the first manufacturer in the LMDh ruleset to select Oreca as their partner.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-06] It was also confirmed on the same day that Meyer Shank Racing and Wayne Taylor Racing would campaign the ARX-06 in the 2023 IMSA SportsCar Championship season.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-06] The ARX-06 completed its first shakedown at Circuit Paul Ricard in July 2022.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-06] It was followed by the car's first full test at Circuit de Nevers Magny-Cours on 16 & 17 July 2022.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-06] The car was revealed on August 17, 2022.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-06] It was also announced that the car would use a hybrid powertrain, consisting of a 90° twin-turbocharged V6 internal combustion engine and standardized hybrid drivetrain components provided by Williams Advanced Engineering, Bosch and Xtrac, for maximum possible combined output of 671 hp (500 KW).
[src:astemo/acura-arx-06] No 24 hour tests were conducted due to supply-chain issues.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-06] Two ARX-06s would campaign the 2023 IMSA SportsCar Championship.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-06] Wayne Taylor Racing and Meyer Shank Racing returned to compete with Acura after both teams had been competing in the series with Acura's ARX-05 since 2021.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-06] Wayne Taylor Racing, entering a partnership with Andretti Global for 2023, continued to race as #10, retaining Filipe Albuquerque and Ricky Taylor for the full season, and Meyer Shank Racing carried over #60, with longtime IMSA driver Colin Braun joining a returning Tom Blomqvist.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-06] After the race, Meyer Shank Racing were awarded a 200-point penalty following a post-race investigation by IMSA that revealed the team had manipulated tire pressure data in order to gain an advantage.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-06] They were, however, allowed to keep their race victory, which created controversy amongst drivers and spectators.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-06] Acura would finish 3rd in the Manufacturers' Standings.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-06] At the end of the season, Meyer Shank Racing left the series to focus on an expanded effort in the 2024 IndyCar Series.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-06] With Meyer Shank Racing's exit, Wayne Taylor Racing took over management of both cars, retaining Filipe Albuquerque and Ricky Taylor to drive the #10 car, and taking on Jordan Taylor and Louis Delétraz to race in the new #40 car.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-06] Acura would fall behind on pace from the front as Porsche and Cadillac regularly fought in the top 5 and BMW would be in the mix.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-06] The #10 crew would earn the team's second victory at the 2024 Chevrolet Detroit Sports Car Classic, with Albuquerque taking advantage of a late drive-through penalty from Porsche's Nick Tandy.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-06] Wayne Taylor Racing would score a total of four podiums and two race wins with the ARX-06, and would finish 5th and 6th in the Drivers' Standings.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-06] Acura would once again finish 3rd in the Manufacturers' Standings.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-06] For 2025, Wayne Taylor Racing would confirm a move to Cadillac, replacing Chip Ganassi Racing, and Meyer Shank Racing would return to the programme, confirming to a two-car lineup for the season, with one of the entries managed by Honda Racing Corporation USA.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-06] Blomqvist and Braun were retained for the full season to drive the returning #60 car, and Nick Yelloly and Renger van der Zande would join from BMW and Cadillac respectively to form the full season lineup for the new #93 car.
[src:astemo/acura-arx-06] IndyCar champions Álex Palou and Scott Dixon would join the team for the Michelin Endurance Cup rounds.
[src:astemo/acura] Acura was the first luxury division established by a Japanese automaker.
[src:astemo/acura] The creation of Acura coincided with the introduction of a JDM Honda dealership sales channel, called Honda Clio, which sold luxury vehicles, joining previously established Honda Verno, followed by Honda Primo the following year.
[src:astemo/acura] In its first few years of existence, Acura was among the best-selling luxury marques in the US, outselling established brands such as BMW and Mercedes-Benz.
[src:astemo/acura] Though sales were down in the mid-to-late 1990s, the brand experienced a revival in the early 2000s, due to drastic redesigns and the introductions of new models.
[src:astemo/acura] In the late 1980s, the success of the company's first flagship vehicle, the Legend, inspired fellow Japanese automakers Toyota and Nissan to launch their own luxury brands, Lexus and Infiniti, respectively.
[src:astemo/acura] The 1990 launch of the NSX, a mid-engine exotic sports car, offered a reliable and practical alternative to exotic European sports cars, and introduced Honda's VTEC variable valve timing system to the North American market.
[src:astemo/acura] The 1993 Legend coupé featured Acura's first use of a six-speed manual transmission mated to a Type II engine.
[src:astemo/acura] In the late 1990s, Acura produced a Type R version of its compact Integra, which featured a reduced curb weight, a stiffer and lower suspension, and a high-output VTEC engine.
[src:astemo/acura] In the early 2000s, Acura introduced new models, including the company's first all-original SUV, the MDX, and two models which replaced the Integra coupé and sedan, the RSX and TSX, respectively.
[src:astemo/acura] Type-S versions of the RSX, CL, and TL were added to the brand's lineup during that decade.
[src:astemo/acura] Acura's 2005 RL flagship introduced SH-AWD, a torque-vectoring all-wheel drive system.
[src:astemo/acura] The 2007 RDX, a crossover SUV, featured the first North American use of a turbocharged Honda engine.
[src:astemo/acura] A second generation NSX was launched in 2016 and features a twin-turbocharged mid-engine, a nine-speed dual-clutch transmission, and Sport Hybrid SH-AWD.
[src:astemo/acura] Two more models were introduced in the mid-2010s—the TLX, which replaced both the TL and TSX, and the RLX, a new flagship.
[src:astemo/acura] In the 2020s, the Type-S marque returned after a long hiatus, and the Integra and ZDX nameplates were revived; the latter is Acura's first electric vehicle.
[src:astemo/acura] The Acura name is derived from the Latin “**acu**tus,” meaning "to sharpen".
[src:astemo/acura] The logo is derived from the caliper, a precise design tool representing the meticulous attention to detail that goes into every car.
[src:astemo/acura] It also closely resembles Honda's "H" logo, with the tops of the side verticals pinched together.
[src:astemo/acura] The brand was created around the same time as Japanese rivals Nissan and Toyota developed their respective Infiniti and Lexus premium brands.
[src:astemo/acura] The Japanese government imposed voluntary export restraints for the U.S. market, so it was more profitable for Japanese automakers to export more expensive cars to the U.S.
[src:astemo/acura] Following a decade of research, Honda opened 60 new dealerships in North America by 1986, to support its Acura automobile division.
[src:astemo/acura] Acura was the first Japanese luxury brand, introduced under the slogan, "Acura.
[src:astemo/acura] Precision Crafted Automobiles." Its initial offering consisted of two models: the executive class Legend and the compact class Integra, available as a five-door and three-door hatchback.
[src:astemo/acura] The Legend was the result of Project XX, a joint venture Honda entered into with the UK's Austin Rover Group.
[src:astemo/acura] It was mechanically related to the Rover 800 series, while the Integra was an improvement of the Honda Quint hatchback.
[src:astemo/acura] Toyota introduced the Lexus ES, Nissan introduced the Infiniti J30 and Ford utilized the Taurus platform and named their new sedan the Lincoln Continental.
[src:astemo/acura] In 1987, Acura's first full year of sales, they sold 109,000 cars with the flagship Legend sedan accounting for 55,000 sales and the rest were of the smaller Integra.
[src:astemo/acura] By 1990, Acura was selling 138,000 vehicles, including 54,000 Legends, compared to Mercedes-Benz's 78,000 cars and 64,000 each for BMW and Lexus.
[src:astemo/acura] In 1990, five years after the debut of the Legend and Integra, Acura introduced the NSX, a midship V6 powered, rear-wheel-drive sports car.
[src:astemo/acura] The NSX, an acronym for "New Sports eXperimental", was billed as the first Japanese car capable of competing with Ferrari and Porsche.
[src:astemo/acura] This vehicle served as an "image car" for both the Honda and Acura brands, heralding the introduction of Honda's VTEC technology.
[src:astemo/acura] The NSX was the world's first all-aluminum production car, and was also marketed and viewed by some as the "everyday supercar" thanks in part to its ease of use, quality and reliability, traits that were unheard of in the supercar segment at the time.
[src:astemo/acura] With the release of the NSX, Acura introduced the "A-badge", a stylized pair of calipers—a tool used for exacting measurements to imply that Acura vehicles are built to precise and demanding standards.
[src:astemo/acura] Despite a strong start in market acceptance for the Acura brand, sales suffered in the mid-to-late 1990s.
[src:astemo/acura] Some critics attributed this decline in part to less inspiring designs, which were re-branded Japanese-spec Hondas, such as the Acura Vigor in 1992.
[src:astemo/acura] Additionally, during this time Acura switched to an alphanumeric nomenclature formula, dropping the Legend, Vigor and Integra titles, following the lead of the NSX sportscar.
[src:astemo/acura] The parent company, Honda, was also feeling the results of the decline of the Japanese economy, due to the Japanese asset price bubble that took place during the 1990s and into the 2000s.
[src:astemo/acura] This period is known in Japan as the Lost Decade.
[src:astemo/acura] During this time, the NSX also lost sales as Acura made few changes from its original 1990 trim.
[src:astemo/acura] A year later, the Integra sedan was withdrawn from the Canadian market, replaced by the market-exclusive Acura 1.6 EL, a rebadged Honda Civic/Domani.
[src:astemo/acura] The Integra sedan continued to be sold in the United States until 2001 (in name only, the model it was replaced with, the RSX, was simply a rebadged left-hand-drive version of the JDM DC5 Honda Integra).
[src:astemo/acura] Despite these letdowns, Acura gained prominence in the 1990s with a young group of customers: "tuner" enthusiasts.
[src:astemo/acura] Parent company Honda's reputation with this demographic as a maker of "easy-to-tune" and "rev-happy" engines rubbed off onto Acura, and the Integra became a popular tuner car.
[src:astemo/acura] Beginning around the year 2000, Acura experienced a rebirth which was catalyzed by the introduction of several redesigned models.
[src:astemo/acura] The first of these models was the 1999 Acura 3.2 TL, an upscale sedan.
[src:astemo/acura] Critics suggested that although 3.2 TL did not outdo its competition in any one area of luxury cars, it offered a well-rounded blend of sportiness and luxury.
[src:astemo/acura] These characteristics, combined with the TL's competitive price, proved very popular with consumers.
[src:astemo/acura] Subsequent Acura models have followed a similar philosophy of offering much standard equipment and few options.
[src:astemo/acura] Another refreshed Acura introduced in the early 2000s was the MDX, a popular three-row crossover SUV based on the Honda Odyssey minivan.
[src:astemo/acura] The MDX replaced the slow-selling SLX, which was little more than a rebadged Isuzu Trooper.
[src:astemo/acura] The MDX was a car-like crossover SUV with limited off-road capability that catered to the demands of the luxury SUV market.
[src:astemo/acura] It was given top honors by Car and Driver in its first comparison test against seven other SUVs.
[src:astemo/acura] Other cars in Acura's line-up during this time included the 3.2 TL, 3.2 CL, RSX (formerly the Integra hatchback), and the NSX.
[src:astemo/acura] By the late 2000s, Acura had dropped the inclusion of engine displacement numbers in its vehicle designations, retaining a simpler, two- or three-letter designation instead (e.g.
[src:astemo/acura] The 1999-2003 TL have been plagued by transmission and other problems.
[src:astemo/acura] In 2001, a new coupe, badged as the RSX was introduced to the Acura line up.
[src:astemo/acura] It was a replacement for the outgoing Integra.
[src:astemo/acura] The RSX is a rebadged Honda Integra (DC5) from the Japanese market.
[src:astemo/acura] As a result, the RSX is technically a new generation of the outgoing Integra.
[src:astemo/acura] Much like the Integra, the RSX was a hit in the tuner market.
[src:astemo/acura] However, at the end of 2006, the RSX was taken out of the Acura line up, subsequently in the Japanese market as well.
[src:astemo/acura] It is not known why the RSX did not continue to be sold as the Integra in Japan, however, the reason that Acura gave for the cancellation of the RSX is that Acura wishes to move up in the luxury brand, thus cannot sell a car that is mostly driven by teenagers.
[src:astemo/acura] A new TL was introduced for the 2004 model year, with a 270 hp (200 kW) V6 measured by the then-current SAE standards.
[src:astemo/acura] The new TL increased sales dramatically to 70,943 American units in 2005.
[src:astemo/acura] Also around the same time the Acura TSX was introduced.
[src:astemo/acura] It was essentially a re-badged European and Japanese market Honda Accord loaded with features.
[src:astemo/acura] This model became the only 4-cylinder sedan in Acura's line-up (with the exception of the Canadian market Acura CSX, which replaced the EL in 2006).
[src:astemo/acura] Acura's new models—particularly the TL and TSX—were well received by the motoring press and became Acura's top selling vehicles by then.
[src:astemo/acura] The TSX was on *Car and Driver*'s Ten Best list from 2004 to 2006.
[src:astemo/acura] In 2005, a new RL was introduced with a 300 hp (220 kW) V6, improved styling, and Super Handling All-Wheel Drive (SH-AWD), a system capable of sending almost all of the RL's power to just one wheel in a turn.
[src:astemo/acura] The second-generation RL appeared on *Car and Driver*'s Ten Best list for 2005, and also garnered an CNET.com "Editor's Choice".
[src:astemo/acura] However in the midsize luxury segment, RL sales lagged far behind not only the best-selling German offerings but also Japanese contemporaries like the Lexus GS and Infiniti M.
[src:astemo/acura] Honda Japan had set the RL's initial price high, close to those with V8 engines, disappointing potential customers who perceived Acura as not being on par with its German rivals in brand equity and expected more value from the Japanese marque.
[src:astemo/acura] The damage from Honda Japan's alleged hubris was done, even though Honda Canada has since reduced the RL's price.
[src:astemo/acura] In 2006 Acura introduced a compact crossover SUV which was based on its own unique unibody chassis called the RDX with models becoming available to U.S. consumers in August 2006.
[src:astemo/acura] It is powered by a turbocharged 240-hp 4-cylinder engine and, like the RL, uses Acura's SH-AWD system.
[src:astemo/acura] A completely redesigned MDX became available in the fall of 2006 with a 300 hp (220 kW) V6 engine and Super Handling All-Wheel Drive.
[src:astemo/acura] Acura reintroduced the TL Type-S for the 2007 model year.
[src:astemo/acura] 2009 marked the all new TL and TSX models as well as a mid-year model update for the RL; all three made their debuts in the 2008 calendar year.
[src:astemo/acura] Acura planned on redesigning the RL by 2011 as well as announced the creation of a brand new luxury crossover vehicle called the ZDX, previewed by the concept of the same name.
[src:astemo/acura] The ZDX was the first vehicle designed in Acura's design studio located in Torrance, California.
[src:astemo/acura] The ZDX was designed by Michelle Christensen, and based on the Acura MDX using that vehicle's 3.7 litre V6 engine (300 bhp) and SH-AWD system.
[src:astemo/acura] It is also the first Acura to be completely built in North America.
[src:astemo/acura] The production model of the ZDX made its debut in the Orange County Auto Show in Southern California on 15 October 2009.
[src:astemo/acura] The concept behind the ZDX is that it is a "four door coupe," and the design emphasis of the body of the car is like a "pulled back slingshot." Another prominent design aspect of the ZDX is the wide rear shoulders above the rear wheels.
[src:astemo/acura] Acura initially had plans for the third generation of RL to be a rear wheel drive V8 sedan for its flagship, but shelved the plans in the wake of the 2008 economic downturn.
[src:astemo/acura] Acura announced new TSX wagon in the 2010 New York Auto Show and went on sale in Fall of 2010.
[src:astemo/acura] The wagon version of the TSX is based on the wagon version of the Euro-spec Honda Accord which has been in the European market for some time.
[src:astemo/acura] However, Acura did not announce any plans for the third-generation RL.
[src:astemo/acura] For the 2010 model year the MDX models received some slight exterior changes and increased equipment levels.
[src:astemo/acura] Mechanically the engine remained unchanged but the transmission was updated from the previous 5-speeds to 6-speeds including steering column mounted shift override paddles.
[src:astemo/acura] This new transmission was shared with the ZDX.
[src:astemo/acura] In 2012, Acura introduced a new model called the ILX which replaced the Acura CSX in Canada and is based on the Honda Civic platform.
[src:astemo/acura] It also unveiled the Acura RLX Concept, a replacement for the RL sedan, at the New York International Auto Show.
[src:astemo/acura] The ILX went on sale in May 2012 in the United States as a 2013 model.
[src:astemo/acura] Also in 2012, Acura "reinvented" another model, The RDX concept.
[src:astemo/acura] For the new model, Acura dropped the 4 cylinder turbo for a 3.5L V6.
[src:astemo/acura] When the official 2013 Acura RDX was released, it was relatively similar to the concept but had changes in wheels, taillights, and some other cosmetics.
[src:astemo/acura] A lot of this Acura looks like its brother the ILX.
[src:astemo/acura] The 2013 RDX doesn't have the SH-AWD system instead it has "AWD with intelligent control", similar to the CR-V's AWD system.
[src:astemo/acura] In 2013, Acura showed a 2014 Concept of the MDX.
[src:astemo/acura] Shortly after, it was released to the public.
[src:astemo/acura] The MDX competes with the Lexus RX, Audi Q7, and many others.
[src:astemo/acura] In December 2013, at the Los Angeles Auto Show, Acura unveiled a Sport Hybrid SH-AWD version of the flagship RLX sedan.
[src:astemo/acura] It has a 310-horsepower 3.5L V6 engine and a pair of electric motors (one for each axle) that generate a combined 377 horsepower through a new 7-speed dual clutch transmission.
[src:astemo/acura] The new RLX Sport Hybrid will go on sale in mid-2014.
[src:astemo/acura] In January 2014, at the Detroit Auto Show, Acura unveiled the all-new 2015 TLX sports sedan.
[src:astemo/acura] This new vehicle replaced the soon to be discontinued TSX and TL sedans.
[src:astemo/acura] The TLX in the 2.4-liter comes with Acura's all new eight-speed dual clutch DCT transmission.
[src:astemo/acura] Meanwhile, the high-end 3.5-liter V6 model came with the new nine-speed transmission and Super-Handling All Wheel Drive (SH-AWD).
[src:astemo/acura] The TLX went on sale in the Summer of 2014.
[src:astemo/acura] In 2015, Acura redesigned the ILX for the 2016 model year.
[src:astemo/acura] Now solely available with a 2.4L K24V7 engine and 8-speed dual clutch transmission (DCT) instead of the 2.0L R20A1 & 5-speed automatic transmission, 2.4L K24Z7 6 speed manual transmission and hybrid electric options.
[src:astemo/acura] Featured with the same 3.5L 6-speed automatic with some slight adjustments for efficiency and hp/torque boosts.
[src:astemo/acura] The RDX gets the Acura Jewel Eye LED treatment as well.
[src:astemo/acura] A new Advance Package is being offered with the inclusion of, parking sensors (front and rear), rain-sensing windshield wipers, auto-dimming side mirrors, remote start, ventilated seats, and foglights.
[src:astemo/acura] In 2017, Acura made considerations on opening an Indian branch.
[src:astemo/acura] Almost since its inception, Acura has been involved in American motorsports, specifically in Sports Car Club of America (SCCA) and IMSA GT Championship series.
[src:astemo/acura] Starting in 1991, Acura reached an agreement with Comptech Racing to use the V6 motor of the Acura NSX in Comptech's Camel Lights Spice prototype.
[src:astemo/acura] Acura would go on to take the Lights championship in its initial year, including a class win at the 24 Hours of Daytona.
[src:astemo/acura] Acura and Comptech would take the Lights championships again in 1992 and 1993, as well as another Daytona class win in 1992 and a class win at the 12 Hours of Sebring for 1993.
[src:astemo/acura] However a change in the IMSA rules would lead to the demise of the Camel Lights, and so Acura moved to touring car racing, joining Realtime Racing in the SCCA World Challenge with the NSX in 1996, winning the final two races of the season.
[src:astemo/acura] In 1997, Acura added Acura Integras to the lower classes, and were successful in taking the championship in both of these classes.
[src:astemo/acura] Realtime took the touring championship with the Integra again in 1998, and came within a few points of winning it again in 1999 only to lose it in the final race, then coming back to retake the title in 2000.
[src:astemo/acura] Although Realtime had abandoned the NSX program in 1998, the NSXs returned to the top class in 2001.
[src:astemo/acura] Although the NSX squad suffered mechanical woes and were unable to take the title, the Integras of the touring class once again took the teams championship.
[src:astemo/acura] By 2002, Acura replaced the aged Integra with the RSX in the final races of the season, scoring good finishes in their debut.
[src:astemo/acura] At the same time, Acura finally retired the NSXs from the top GT class.
[src:astemo/acura] The RSXs would later be joined by new Acura TSXs in 2004.
[src:astemo/acura] Realtime continues to campaign the RSX and TSX in the SCCA Speed World Challenge.
[src:astemo/acura] Acura also currently races RSXs and TSXs in the Grand American Road Racing Association's KONI Challenge Series for touring cars.
[src:astemo/acura] At the Detroit Auto Show in 2006, Acura announced their plans to enter the American Le Mans Series with multiple teams of Le Mans prototypes in the LMP2 class starting in 2007 season.
[src:astemo/acura] The cars would be purchased chassis from existing manufacturers, but use American-built Acura V8s (a first for Acura and Honda).
[src:astemo/acura] Acura also announced their initiative to take the cars to the 24 Hours of Le Mans in 2008 and eventually move to the superior LMP1 class with cars built by Acura themselves in 2009.
[src:astemo/acura] Later in 2006, Acura announced that the three factory teams would be Andretti Green Racing, Fernández Racing, and Highcroft Racing, and that the chassis would be built by Lola Cars of the UK and Courage Compétition of France.
[src:astemo/acura] The three Acura-powered prototypes debuted at the 2007 12 Hours of Sebring, which was the opening round of the ALMS season, and were successful in their debut.
[src:astemo/acura] Andretti Green's Acura took second place overall and first in the LMP2 class, while Fernández Racing took third overall, and Highcroft sixth, beating a series of established Porsche teams in their class.
[src:astemo/acura] At the same time, Acura began development of their own chassis by heavily modifying their purchased Courage chassis.
[src:astemo/acura] The cars now have been so radically changed from their original orientation that they are now named Acura ARX-01a.
[src:astemo/acura] Acura will introduce evolved B-spec cars in the 2008 season, with Gil de Ferran launching a fourth Acura team in the ALMS.
[src:astemo/acura] In 2009, Acura produced its first LMP1 car, the Acura ARX-02a.
[src:astemo/acura] In 2010, Honda rebadged all Acura prototypes as Honda Performance Development (HPD) cars, and announced that all future prototypes (such as the HPD ARX-03) would be constructed under the HPD name.
[src:astemo/acura] Acura did not participate in motorsports again until 2013, where two Acura ILXs were unofficially entered in the 25 Hours of Thunderhill by Honda R&D Americas designers and engineers (Team Honda Research West).
[src:astemo/acura] The car would retire from the race due to engine problems.
[src:astemo/acura] The Acura ILXs returned to Thunderhill for the 2014 25-hour race.
[src:astemo/acura] This time the car won its class and finished 8th overall.
[src:astemo/acura] At the 2016 New York International Auto Show, Acura announced the GT3 version of the NSX, which began competition in 2017 with factory support in both WeatherTech SportsCar Championship's GTD class and Pirelli World Challenge GT class, the latter replacing the Acura TLX.
[src:astemo/acura] The car competes under Honda branding outside North America.
[src:astemo/acura] The Acura logo, introduced in 1990 for the 1991 model year, is, according to Honda, a caliper — a design tool used for measuring that can also be interpreted as a skewed "H" (for Honda) or a stylised "A" (for Acura).
[src:astemo/acura] The logo that was originally authorized without approval by Soichiro Honda did not contain the small horizontal bar joining the two vertical pillars—thus, it did not form the letter "H".
[src:astemo/acura] Soichiro Honda ordered the 5,000 badges already produced to be destroyed, including prying off the emblems applied to 309 cars already (US-spec Integra, Legend, and NSX models).
[src:astemo/acura] Acura's current marketing slogan is "Precision Crafted Performance." Recent models include Technology, Advance, Type-S, SH-AWD and A-Spec trim levels.
[src:astemo/acura] Technology and Advance models typically come with the latest hi-tech features such as keyless start and a blind spot information system.
[src:astemo/acura] Type-S and SH-AWD models are performance-oriented, with a substantial increase in horsepower compared to the lower trim levels.
[src:astemo/acura] Some models, such as the TL, also combine trim levels (i.e.
[src:astemo/acura] Acura began an association with Marvel Entertainment in 2010, upon release of the film *Iron Man 2*, which featured a ZDX after the ending credits.
[src:astemo/acura] On April 20, 2011, Acura and Marvel announced a promotional campaign, making Acura the official brand of Marvel's fictional S.H.I.E.L.D. organization.
[src:astemo/acura] Soon thereafter, several Acura models—such as the MDX, ZDX, RL, and TL—appeared in the films *Thor* and *Captain America: The First Avenger*.
[src:astemo/acura] In the 2012 film, *The Avengers*, Iron Man (played by Robert Downey Jr.) drove an exotic sportscar by Acura, made specifically for the film, rather than the Audi R8 he previously drove.
[src:astemo/acura] It was rumored that the car spotted during filming was a concept for the second generation NSX, however, a different-looking 2012 Acura NSX Concept was unveiled at the North American International Auto Show, on 9 January 2012.
[src:astemo/acura] From 1995 to 2007, Acura sponsored two WTA Tour tennis tournaments, both named the Acura Classic.
[src:astemo/acura] In 2012, Acura was the presenting sponsor and official vehicle of the Sundance Film Festival.
[src:astemo/acura] Acura also has a 'Mobility Program' that ensures drivers who are disabled are safe in their vehicles.
[src:astemo/acura] The program offers cash reimbursement towards the cost of adaptive equipment for disabled drivers.
[src:astemo/acura] Acura was the official shirt sponsor of the Columbus Crew from 2017 to 2020.
[src:astemo/asimo] E0 was the first bipedal model produced as part of the Honda E series, which was an early experimental line of self-regulating walking robots with wireless movements created between 1986 and 1993.
[src:astemo/asimo] This was followed by the Honda P series of robots produced from 1993 through 1997.
[src:astemo/asimo] The research made on the E- and P-series led to the creation of ASIMO.
[src:astemo/asimo] Development began at Honda's Wako Fundamental Technical Research Center in Japan in 1999, and ASIMO was unveiled in October 2000.
[src:astemo/asimo] In 2002, 20 units of the first model were produced.
[src:astemo/asimo] In July 2018, Honda stated that it would be ceasing all development and production of ASIMO robots in order to focus on more practical applications using the technology developed through ASIMO's lifespan.
[src:astemo/asimo] It made its last active appearance in March 2022, as Honda announced the retirement of ASIMO to concentrate on remote-controlled, avatar-style robotic technology.
[src:astemo/asimo] ASIMO stands 130 cm (4 ft 3 in) tall and weighs 54 kg (119 lb).
[src:astemo/asimo] Research conducted by Honda found that the ideal height for a mobility assistant robot was between 120 cm and the height of an average adult, which is conducive to operating door knobs and light switches.
[src:astemo/asimo] ASIMO is powered by a rechargeable 51.8 V lithium-ion battery with an operating time of one hour.
[src:astemo/asimo] Switching from a nickel–metal hydride battery in 2004 increased the amount of time ASIMO can operate before recharging.
[src:astemo/asimo] ASIMO has a three-dimensional computer processor created by Honda that consists of three stacked dies, a processor, a signal converter, and memory.
[src:astemo/asimo] The computer that controls ASIMO's movement is housed in the robot's waist area and can be controlled using a PC, wireless controller, or voice commands.
[src:astemo/asimo] Using visual information captured by two camera "eyes", ASIMO has the ability to recognize moving objects (and determine their distance and direction), postures, gestures, its surrounding environment, sounds, and faces.
[src:astemo/asimo] Some of these features enable ASIMO to interact with humans, including by facing a person when approached or following them.
[src:astemo/asimo] The robot interprets voice commands and gestures, e.g. enabling it to respond accordingly when a handshake is offered or when a person waves or points.
[src:astemo/asimo] ASIMO's ability to distinguish between voices and other sounds allows it to identify its companions.
[src:astemo/asimo] ASIMO is able to respond to its name and recognizes sounds associated with a falling object or collision.
[src:astemo/asimo] This allows the robot to face a person when spoken to or look towards a sound.
[src:astemo/asimo] ASIMO responds to questions by nodding or providing a verbal answer in different languages and can recognize approximately 10 different faces and address them by name.
[src:astemo/asimo] ASIMO is equipped with sensors that assist in autonomous navigation.
[src:astemo/asimo] The two cameras inside its head act as visual sensors to detect obstacles.
[src:astemo/asimo] The lower portion of the torso has two ground sensors—one laser sensor and one infrared sensor.
[src:astemo/asimo] The laser sensor is used to detect the ground surface, and the infrared sensor with automatic shutter adjustment based on brightness is used to detect pairs of floor markings to navigate along paths.
[src:astemo/asimo] A pre-loaded map and the detection of floor markings help the robot to precisely identify its present location and continuously adjust its position.
[src:astemo/asimo] There are front and rear ultrasonic sensors to sense obstacles; the front sensor is located at the lower torso together with the ground sensors, and the rear sensor is located at the bottom of the "backpack".
[src:astemo/asimo] Honda's work with ASIMO led to further research on walking assist devices, resulting in the Stride Management Assist and Bodyweight Support Assist prototypes.
[src:astemo/asimo] In 2004, ASIMO was inducted into the Carnegie Mellon Robot Hall of Fame.
[src:astemo/asimo] In honor of ASIMO's 10th anniversary in November 2010, Honda developed a mobile app called "Run with ASIMO", wherein users learn about the robot by virtually walking it through the steps of a race and then sharing their lap times on Twitter and Facebook.
[src:astemo/asimo] ASIMO was also the inspiration behind the 2012 film *Robot & Frank*, wherein a similar humanoid robot, portrayed by an actress in a costume, assists an aging cat burglar.
[src:astemo/asimo] Since ASIMO was introduced in 2000, the robot has traveled around the world and performed in front of international audiences.
[src:astemo/asimo] ASIMO made its first public appearance in the United States in 2002 when it rang the bell to open trade sessions for the New York Stock Exchange.
[src:astemo/asimo] The robot first visited the United Kingdom in January 2003 for private demonstrations at the Science Museum in London.
[src:astemo/asimo] ASIMO continued on a world tour, making stops in countries such as Spain, the United Arab Emirates, Russia, South Africa, and Australia.
[src:astemo/asimo] From January 2003 to March 2005, the robot toured the US and Canada, demonstrating its abilities for more than 130,000 people.
[src:astemo/asimo] From 2003 to 2004, ASIMO was part of a North American educational tour, where it visited top science and technology museums and academic institutions throughout North America.
[src:astemo/asimo] The goal of the tour was to encourage students to study science through a live show that highlighted ASIMO's abilities.
[src:astemo/asimo] Additionally, the robot visited top engineering and computer science colleges and universities across the US as part of the ASIMO Technology Circuit Tour in an effort to encourage students to consider scientific careers.
[src:astemo/asimo] In March 2005, ASIMO walked the red carpet at the world premiere of the animated film *Robots*.
[src:astemo/asimo] In June of that year, the robot became a feature in a show called "Say 'Hello' to Honda's ASIMO" at Disneyland's Innoventions attraction, which was a part of the Tomorrowland area of the park.
[src:astemo/asimo] This was the only permanent installation of ASIMO in North America until Innoventions was closed in April 2015.
[src:astemo/asimo] In a demonstration at Honda's Tokyo headquarters in 2007, the company demonstrated new intelligence technologies that enabled multiple ASIMO robots to work together.
[src:astemo/asimo] The demonstration showed the robot's ability to identify and avoid oncoming people, work with another ASIMO, recognize when to recharge its battery, and perform new tasks such as carrying a tray and pushing a cart.
[src:astemo/asimo] In October 2008, ASIMO greeted Prince Charles during a visit to the Miraikan museum in Tokyo, where it performed a seven-minute step and dance routine.
[src:astemo/asimo] In 2014, then–US President Barack Obama was introduced to ASIMO at Miraikan.
[src:astemo/asimo] In 2008, ASIMO conducted the Detroit Symphony Orchestra in a performance of "The Impossible Dream" to bring attention to its partnership with the orchestra and support performing arts in Detroit.
[src:astemo/asimo] A 49-foot replica of ASIMO made with natural materials, such as lettuce seed, rice and carnations, led the 120th Rose Parade in celebration of Honda's 50th year of operation in the US.
[src:astemo/asimo] Later that year, the robot made an appearance at the Genoa Science Festival in Italy.
[src:astemo/asimo] In January 2010, Honda debuted a 10-minute documentary at the Sundance Film Festival that focuses on the experience of human interaction with robots like ASIMO.
[src:astemo/asimo] The robot attended the Ars Electronica festival in Linz, Austria, in September 2010, which allowed Honda to study the results of human–robot interaction and use the results to guide development of future versions of the robot.
[src:astemo/asimo] In April 2011, ASIMO was demonstrated at the FIRST Championship in St.
[src:astemo/asimo] Louis, Missouri, to encourage students to pursue studies in math, science and engineering.
[src:astemo/asimo] That November, ASIMO was one of the star attractions at the first Abu Dhabi Science Festival.
[src:astemo/asimo] ASIMO visited the Ontario Science Center in Toronto in May 2011 and demonstrated its abilities to Canadian students.
[src:astemo/asimo] The robot later traveled to Ottawa for the unveiling of an exhibit at the Canadian Museum of Civilization 19 May through 22 May 2011.
[src:astemo/asimo] ASIMO appeared as a guest on the British quiz show *QI* on 2 December 2011.
[src:astemo/asimo] After serving water to host Stephen Fry and dancing with comedian Jo Brand, ASIMO won with 32 points.
[src:astemo/asimo] On 24 March 2017, Honda revealed ASIMO in Disneyland's Autopia attraction.
[src:astemo/asimo] On multiple occasions, audience members at public showcasings of ASIMO have filmed the robot malfunctioning and falling down stairs.
[src:astemo/asimo] These videos have been uploaded on YouTube, and some have become viral for their comedic nature.
[src:astemo/astemo] The company name was changed from **Hitachi Astemo, Ltd.** to Astemo, Ltd. on April 1, 2025.
[src:astemo/astemo] Astemo was established in January 2021 as a global automotive components manufacturer through the business merger of Hitachi Automotive Systems, Keihin Corporation, Showa Corporation, and Nissin Kogyo.
[src:astemo/astemo] The name "Astemo" stands for "Advanced Sustainable Technologies for Mobility", reflecting the company's focus on technologies related to connected, autonomous, shared and electric mobility.
[src:astemo/astemo] Astemo develops automotive technologies aligned with the industry trends of connectivity, autonomous systems and electrification, with a focus on both passenger and motorcycle applications.
[src:astemo/astemo] Astemo's ownership structure includes major stakes from both Hitachi, Ltd. and Honda Motor Co., Ltd., each holding 40%, with JIC Capital holding the remaining 20%.
[src:astemo/astemo] While Astemo includes former Honda-affiliated parts manufacturers, it also maintains business relationships with Nissan Motor Co., reflecting Hitachi's historical ties to the Nissan Group.
[src:astemo/astemo] In December 2025, Honda announced it would acquire an additional 21% of Astemo shares from Hitachi.
[src:astemo/astemo] As a result, the shareholding structure of Astemo will change to 61% for Honda, 20% for JIC, and 19% for Hitachi.
[src:astemo/astemo] Astemo has expanded its research and development activities in electric powertrains, advanced driver-assistance systems, and in-vehicle software.
[src:astemo/astemo] These efforts support its strategic focus on electrification and autonomous mobility.
[src:astemo/astemo] The company has also pursued partnerships and vertical integration to address industry competition and supply chain challenges.
[src:astemo/astemo] In December 2024, the Government of Cantabria awarded the Hitachi Astemo Buelna plant a €1 million grant through SODERCAN’s competitive programme for major industrial competitiveness projects.
[src:astemo/astemo] The funding supports a €5 million experimental development project focused on advanced braking systems, to be completed over 18 months.
[src:astemo/astemo] This initiative underlines the region’s strategic support for automotive innovation and sustainability efforts.
[src:astemo/astemo] Astemo develops components for electric and autonomous vehicles, with a focus on integration of key systems such as power control units, motors, inverters, and software-defined vehicle platforms.
[src:astemo/astemo] The company also emphasizes model-based systems engineering and virtual validation to shorten development timelines and reduce prototyping costs.
[src:astemo/astemo] In 2023, Astemo announced a ¥15.3 billion (~US $100 million) expansion of its Berea, Kentucky plant to support its electrification business.
[src:astemo/astemo] In July 2025, Astemo announced a £100 million investment in its Horwich manufacturing facility in Bolton, Greater Manchester.
[src:astemo/astemo] The project will establish a new production line dedicated to electric vehicle (EV) inverters, making the site the only facility in the United Kingdom with this production capability.
[src:astemo/astemo] As of 2025, Astemo operates over 100 business sites globally, including manufacturing plants, R&D centers and regional offices across Asia, Europe and the Americas.
[src:astemo/astemo] Astemo's facilities span over 25 countries, including sites in Mexico, France, Brazil, Thailand and Vietnam.
[src:astemo/astemo] A complete list is available on the Astemo Global Network.
[src:astemo/astemo] In September 2025, *CBS News* and *The Detroit News* reported that Astemo planned to establish a regional headquarters in Wixom, Michigan, as part of a $95 million investment expected to create about 200 jobs.
[src:astemo/astemo] Hitachi Astemo sponsors Team Penske in NTT IndyCar Series in the U.S.A.
[src:astemo/astemo] Astemo also sponsors Real Racing in the Super GT GT500 class and S.I.
[src:astemo/astemo] RACING in the MFJ All Japan Road Race Championship Series.
[src:astemo/astemo] Astemo owns the Japanese women's volleyball team "Hitachi Astemo Rivale" and sponsors Mie Honda Heat, a Japanese rugby union team based in Suzuka City.
[src:astemo/astemo] On December 21, 2021, Hitachi Astemo admitted to falsifying inspection data on brake and suspension components.
[src:astemo/astemo] Over 50,000 instances of improper testing were identified, dating back to 2003.
